316
00:18:17,929 --> 00:18:22,993
One term that is mentioned over and over again in level design is this term called moment-to-moment

317
00:18:23,013 --> 00:18:23,454
gameplay.

318
00:18:23,514 --> 00:18:27,117
What happens from one moment to the other moment as the player is playing through the

319
00:18:27,137 --> 00:18:27,377
level?

320
00:18:27,977 --> 00:18:32,661
In our case, because most of our games are turn-based, I like to term this as our turn-to-turn

321
00:18:32,681 --> 00:18:33,062
gameplay.

322
00:18:33,882 --> 00:18:35,904
And this is where the concept of level flow comes in.

323
00:18:38,290 --> 00:18:38,791
So flow.

324
00:18:40,111 --> 00:18:42,212
The concept of level flow is the concept

325
00:18:42,572 --> 00:18:45,074
of how to keep players moving forward towards the goal.

326
00:18:45,494 --> 00:18:47,975
In traditional games, you use concepts like signposting,

327
00:18:48,035 --> 00:18:50,696
like goals and sub-goals, or some sort of hint system.

328
00:18:51,357 --> 00:18:54,418
What Edburns says in his book is that the level designer

329
00:18:54,458 --> 00:18:57,319
is the invisible hand that guides the players forward.

330
00:18:57,620 --> 00:18:59,841
But the more aware that the players are of this hand,

331
00:18:59,881 --> 00:19:00,901
the less fun that it will be.

332
00:19:01,761 --> 00:19:02,882
So this is a little bit of a paradox.

333
00:19:04,804 --> 00:19:08,845
An example of level flow in one of our games, again coming back to Candy Crush Soda,

334
00:19:08,865 --> 00:19:11,326
